      Stimwave
   =20
 =20

If you trick people into getting unnecessary surgeries to implant fake medi=
cal devices in their bodies, is that securities fraud? Obviously you know t=
he answer =E2=80=94=C2=A0everything is securities fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0but =
doesn=E2=80=99t that seem=C2=A0more=C2=A0like something=C2=A0else? Like if =
you go around tricking people into getting surgeries to implant fake medica=
l devices in their bodies, doesn=E2=80=99t it seem like the=C2=A0victims=C2=
=A0are mostly the patients? The people you tricked into implanting fake med=
ical devices?
But the US Securities and Exchange Commission regulates securities fraud, n=
ot surgeries, so here is  an=C2=A0SEC lawsuit against Laura Perryman, the f=
ormer chief executive officer of Stimwave Technologies Inc.:

The Securities and Exchange Commission [Dec. 19] charged Laura Tyler Perrym=
an, the former CEO and co-founder of Florida-based medical device startup S=
timwave Technologies Inc., with defrauding investors out of approximately $=
41 million by making false and misleading statements about one of the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s key medical device products. According to the SEC=E2=80=99s co=
mplaint, the medical device comprised several components, one of which was =
a fake, non-functional component that was implanted into patients=E2=80=99 =
bodies. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CWe allege that Perryman touted a supposedly innovative medical pai=
n-relief device while concealing that a primary component of the device was=
 fake and that patients were unwittingly undergoing unnecessary surgeries t=
o implant the non-functional component into their bodies,=E2=80=9D said Mon=
ique C. Winkler, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s San Francisco Regional Offic=
e. =E2=80=9CInvestors are entitled to know material information about the p=
roducts of the companies in which they invest. The SEC is committed to hold=
ing bad actors accountable.=E2=80=9D

Meanwhile there was an earlier  federal criminal case against Perryman, but=
 there again the victims were not the=C2=A0patients, who got fake medical d=
evices implanted in their bodies, but rather=C2=A0Medicare=C2=A0and insuran=
ce companies, who paid for it.
From the  criminal indictment, you can sort of see why. Stimwave built a=C2=
=A0working=C2=A0medical device, consisting of (1) an =E2=80=9Cimplantable e=
lectrode array (the =E2=80=98Lead=E2=80=99) that stimulated the nerve,=E2=
=80=9D (2) an externally worn battery, and (3) a =E2=80=9Ca separate implan=
table receiver measuring approximately 23 cm in length with a distinctive p=
ink handle,=E2=80=9D with a copper antenna that transmitted energy from the=
 battery to the lead. Doctors would implant the lead and the receiver in th=
e patient=E2=80=99s body, the patient would wear the battery, and the whole=
 thing would stimulate the nerve and, I suppose, cure the pain.
But the pink-handled receiver was too long to fit into some people=E2=80=99=
s bodies. =E2=80=9CThe Device could function without a receiver, so long as=
 the Battery was placed close enough to the Lead,=E2=80=9D so doctors could=
 have just implanted the lead and left out the receiver. This would have be=
en fine medically, but it would not have worked financially: Stimwave=C2=A0=
charged $16,000 for the product, and doctors could bill insurers $4,000 to =
$6,000 for implanting the lead and $16,000 to $18,000 for implanting the re=
ceiver. Implant them both, bill $20,000 or so, cover the cost, make a profi=
t, everything works. But without implanting the receiver, the business didn=
=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0
So Stimwave developed another, smaller receiver, which (1) had a white hand=
le and (2) didn=E2=80=99t do anything =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was just plastic, n=
o copper, so it didn=E2=80=99t actually transmit any energy. It was implant=
ed into patients purely to extract $16,000 from their insurers to make the =
whole trade work financially.
I suppose the SEC is right that investors were entitled to know this? And I=
 suppose the Justice Department is right that the insurers were defrauded? =
Still I wonder about the patients. Shouldn=E2=80=99t they have gotten some =
disclosure? But also, what would they have done with full disclosure? Like =
imagine you went to your doctor complaining of chronic pain, and she was li=
ke =E2=80=9CI have a device that can cure you. It=E2=80=99s this electrode =
array that I will implant in your body, and a battery that you will wear to=
 power it. Those two things will fix your pain. I will also, however, have =
to implant an irrelevant piece of plastic into your body, because that will=
 trick your insurance into paying for it.=E2=80=9D You might take that trad=
e, right?

