  [1] In fact, Lee and his team at Parallaxes helped explain them to me at =
the time.


  [2] This is loose and oversimplified, and in fact there are more baroque =
ways to come into a TRA, but this is the sort of normal approach, and what =
we discussed in the case of Sculptor.


  [3] I am interpreting a bit, but I get this from pages 19 and 20 of  the =
D1 complaint, which quotes the terms of the bonds. Note that there are two =
sources of the discount: The notes convert =E2=80=9Can amount equal to 107%=
 of the Original Principal Amount=E2=80=9D into stock, effectively giving t=
he note holders a 7% bonus on their money, and then also they convert at a =
conversion price equal to the new-money investment price =E2=80=9Cmultiplie=
d by the Applicable Discount.=E2=80=9D The discount is redacted, and there =
are valuation floors and caps that are also redacted, but this is the idea.


  [4] Again, pages 18 and 19 of the D1 complaint spell this out.


  [5] Probably? Here=E2=80=99s a 2018 Sports Illustrated article saying: =
=E2=80=9CFor the most part, online presentations of games run 15 seconds to=
 a minute behind the traditional television broadcasts, which themselves ai=
r several seconds after live action. Simple data can be transferred near in=
stantaneously these days, allowing apps like Draftkings Sportsbook to offer=
 pitch-by-pitch odds during the World Series that come in ahead of the play=
 on broadcast television.=E2=80=9D


