<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Stimwave</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you trick people into getting unnecessary s=
urgeries to implant fake medical devices in their bodies, is that securitie=
s fraud? Obviously you know the answer =E2=80=94=C2=A0everything is securit=
ies fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0but doesn=E2=80=99t that seem=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0<=
/em>like something=C2=A0<em>else</em>? Like if you go around tricking peopl=
e into getting surgeries to implant fake medical devices in their bodies, d=
oesn=E2=80=99t it seem like the=C2=A0victims=C2=A0are mostly the patients? =
The people you tricked into implanting fake medical devices?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the US Securities and Exchange Commission =
regulates securities fraud, not surgeries, so here is <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33869100.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmd=
vdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0yNTU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5e09782c"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> an=C2=A0SEC lawsuit</a> against Laura Perryman, the former chief =
executive officer of Stimwave Technologies Inc.:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission [Dec. 1=
9] charged Laura Tyler Perryman, the former CEO and co-founder of Florida-b=
ased medical device startup Stimwave Technologies Inc., with defrauding inv=
estors out of approximately $41 million by making false and misleading stat=
ements about one of the company=E2=80=99s key medical device products. Acco=
rding to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, the medical device comprised several =
components, one of which was a fake, non-functional component that was impl=
anted into patients=E2=80=99 bodies. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe allege that Perryman touted a supp=
osedly innovative medical pain-relief device while concealing that a primar=
y component of the device was fake and that patients were unwittingly under=
going unnecessary surgeries to implant the non-functional component into th=
eir bodies,=E2=80=9D said Monique C. Winkler, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 San Francisco Regional Office. =E2=80=9CInvestors are entitled to know mat=
erial information about the products of the companies in which they invest.=
 The SEC is committed to holding bad actors accountable.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile there was an earlier <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33869100.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cua=
nVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByL2Zvcm1lci1jZW8tbWVkaWNhbC1kZXZpY2UtY29tcGFu=
eS1pbmRpY3RlZC1jcmVhdGluZy1hbmQtc2VsbGluZy1mYWtlLW1lZGljYWwtY29tcG9uZW50/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB43d23fab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> federal criminal case</a> against=
 Perryman, but there again the victims were not the=C2=A0<em>patients</em>,=
 who got fake medical devices implanted in their bodies, but rather=C2=A0<e=
m>Medicare=C2=A0</em>and <em>insurance companies</em>, who paid for it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/33869100.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvZDkvcHJ=
lc3MtcmVsZWFzZXMvYXR0YWNobWVudHMvMjAyMy8wMy8wOS91LnMuX3YuX3BlcnJ5bWFuX2luZG=
ljdG1lbnRfMF8wLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd2fb7889" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> criminal i=
ndictment</a>, you can sort of see why. Stimwave built a=C2=A0<em>working=
=C2=A0</em>medical device, consisting of (1) an =E2=80=9Cimplantable electr=
ode array (the =E2=80=98Lead=E2=80=99) that stimulated the nerve,=E2=80=9D =
(2) an externally worn battery, and (3) a =E2=80=9Ca separate implantable r=
eceiver measuring approximately 23 cm in length with a distinctive pink han=
dle,=E2=80=9D with a copper antenna that transmitted energy from the batter=
y to the lead. Doctors would implant the lead and the receiver in the patie=
nt=E2=80=99s body, the patient would wear the battery, and the whole thing =
would stimulate the nerve and, I suppose, cure the pain.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the pink-handled receiver was too long to =
fit into some people=E2=80=99s bodies. =E2=80=9CThe Device could function w=
ithout a receiver, so long as the Battery was placed close enough to the Le=
ad,=E2=80=9D so doctors could have just implanted the lead and left out the=
 receiver. This would have been fine <em>medically</em>, but it would not h=
ave worked <em>financially: </em>Stimwave=C2=A0charged $16,000 for the prod=
uct, and doctors could bill insurers $4,000 to $6,000 for implanting the le=
ad and $16,000 to $18,000 for implanting the receiver. Implant them both, b=
ill $20,000 or so, cover the cost, make a profit, everything works. But wit=
hout implanting the receiver, the business didn=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Stimwave developed another, smaller receive=
r, which (1) had a white handle and (2) didn=E2=80=99t do anything =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it was just plastic, no copper, so it didn=E2=80=99t actually tran=
smit any energy. It was implanted into patients purely to extract $16,000 f=
rom their insurers to make the whole trade work financially.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose the SEC is right that investors were=
 entitled to know this? And I suppose the Justice Department is right that =
the insurers were defrauded? Still I wonder about the patients. Shouldn=E2=
=80=99t they have gotten some disclosure? But also, what would they have do=
ne with full disclosure? Like imagine you went to your doctor complaining o=
f chronic pain, and she was like =E2=80=9CI have a device that can cure you=
. It=E2=80=99s this electrode array that I will implant in your body, and a=
 battery that you will wear to power it. Those two things will fix your pai=
n. I will also, however, have to implant an irrelevant piece of plastic int=
o your body, because that will trick your insurance into paying for it.=E2=
=80=9D You might take that trade, right?</p>
