om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Juul</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/33869100.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3=
dlYWx0aHktaW52ZXN0b3JzLXJlc2N1ZWQtanV1bC1mcm9tLWJhbmtydXB0Y3ktb3RoZXJzLWFyZ=
S1jcnlpbmctZm91bC01Y2IxODU3OD9tb2Q9bGVhZF9mZWF0dXJlX2JlbG93X2FfcG9zMQ/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBd26c3922" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal article</a> abou=
t how =E2=80=9CWealthy Investors Rescued Juul From Bankruptcy. Others Are C=
rying Foul.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That is, on its face, sort of odd:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two of Juul Labs=E2=80=99 longtime directors=
=E2=80=94a Hyatt Hotels heir and a venture capitalist=E2=80=94helped bail o=
ut the e-cigarette maker when it was on the brink of insolvency.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was a deal that preserved the equity invest=
ments of Nick Pritzker and Riaz Valani, cemented their influence over the c=
ompany and secured them releases from liability in thousands of lawsuits ag=
ainst Juul. Now Juul is fighting a lawsuit from a group of investors allegi=
ng that those two directors were looking out for their own interests, not t=
he company=E2=80=99s.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the questions in dispute is whether the =
bailout that allowed Juul to avert bankruptcy in 2022 benefited insiders at=
 the expense of other investors. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Entities tied to Valani and Pritzker now own n=
early half of Juul, while most other investors have had their stakes sharpl=
y diluted amid the rescue. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Altria=E2=80=99s 2018 investment had set Juul=
=E2=80=99s share price at $279. The investment round that closed in October=
 put it at $1.07.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a somewhat unusual complaint. Ordinarily=
 the thing about bankruptcy is that it wipes out shareholders, so if some s=
hareholders pumped money into Juul to avoid bankruptcy, the=C2=A0<em>other =
</em>shareholders should have no complaints. (They got diluted, sure, but t=
hat=E2=80=99s better than getting zeroed.) And ordinarily the thing about=
=C2=A0<em>averting=C2=A0</em>bankruptcy is that it leaves the debt intact, =
so if some shareholders pumped money into Juul to avoid bankruptcy, its=C2=
=A0<em>creditors=C2=A0</em>should have no complaints. The creditors are sen=
ior to the shareholders, so raising more money from shareholders should be =
strictly good for the creditors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, however, there=E2=80=99s an unusual tric=
k. In 2019 and 2020, Juul issued $2 billion of debt outstanding in the form=
 of convertible bonds. Intuitively the way these bonds work is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They are debt, but</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If Juul goes public, they convert into stock at a =
discount to the initial public offering price.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So basically if you invest $2 billion and thin=
gs go well, you get back, I don=E2=80=99t know, $2.5 billion or so of publi=
c stock; if things go poorly, you get back your $2 billion in cash. And the=
re are a floor and a cap on the conversion price: If Juul goes public at, l=
ike, a $100 billion valuation, you get way more than $2.5 billion worth of =
stock; if it goes public at a tiny valuation, you get less =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ut why would it do that?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But while that is the rough intuition, it is n=
ot=C2=A0<em>exactly=C2=A0</em>what the bonds say. They actually allow the c=
ompany to force conversion into cash upon a =E2=80=9Cqualified financing,=
=E2=80=9D which <em>could=C2=A0</em>be an IPO, but could also be a private =
stock sale that raises at least $500 million from outside sources.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0I suppose that, when you negotiate a bond like this, you think =
=E2=80=9Cwell, if this company is raising $500 million in stock from new eq=
uity investors, that=E2=80=99s probably good news, so I=E2=80=99ll be happy=
 to convert into stock,=E2=80=9D but that=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0<em>necessaril=
y=C2=A0</em>true.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the upshot is that, by raising a bunch =
of money at a 99.6% discount to its peak price, Juul was able to convert $2=
 billion of debt into stock worth much, much less:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Affiliates of hedge fund D1 Capital Partners a=
nd two other investors sued Juul in October 2023 to block a debt conversion=
 triggered by the funding round. The conversion would slash $2 billion in o=
utstanding notes to $116 million in equity, a 94% drop in value, according =
to Juul.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lawsuit alleges that Pritzker and Valani =
=E2=80=9Cleveraged a distressed situation for their own personal gain to th=
e detriment of Juul=E2=80=99s other stakeholders.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/33869100.258411/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb=
2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JRM1BodktHTEc5by92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBab228d5f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> the lawsuit</a>, which basically argues that the=
 rescue financing does not count as a qualified financing (because it was l=
argely funded by insiders) and so shouldn=E2=80=99t trigger their conversio=
n. But that=E2=80=99s the crux of what is going on here: Juul had an opport=
unity to take an equity investment in a way that=C2=A0<em>wiped out its deb=
t</em>, so it did.</p>
